column76:
Involvement corresponds with DDAT (digital, data and technology) skills competency \ Awareness. You know about the skill and have an appreciation of how it is applied in the environment.
Working. You can apply your knowledge and experience of the skill, including tools and techniques. You can adopt those most appropriate for the environment.
Practitioner. You know how to share your knowledge and experience of this skill with others, including tools and techniques. You can define those most appropriate for the environment.
Expert. You have both knowledge and experience in the application of this skill. You are a recognised specialist and adviser in this skill including user needs, generation of ideas, methods and tools. You can lead or guide others in best-practice use.

column75: a bit more introduction to 'data set (csv files) discovery' - meaning, how to separate by either comma, semicolon, tab - if a comma is within a dedicated Column. It messes up the whole spreadsheet if you accidentally choose to separate using a separator that is 'within a column too.' I know OpenRefine & GREL might work, but in the material I do not know how to interpret myself - need a new case, where the data set is poor and 'dirty' within columns, so I can learn to fix this. It seems we get a quite a few data sets from providers, that is looking like this, and it would be nice to be able to clean these data in order to re-use them in other settings
column76:
The lessons and community around (Library) Carpentries helped me to get started, for real, to look deeper into Data Science Skills that can benefit the patrons we support. Being an outreach librarian, teaching and presenting, I love to learn new skills in order to better myself and to become self-confident enough in order to approach both students, teachers, researchers, and administrative staff with the knowledge and skills librarians bring to the table. We have to keep learning as support units, otherwise, we might end up being 'bypassed and forgotten'.
The way the Carpentries introduce new (data) skills are both well planned, with a didactic approach, and presented in a pedagogical manner. It is great for self-studies as well as for groups. I hope all university libraries around the world would consider becoming a member since the skills presented in The Carpentries are super relevant for how scholarly communications and research are evolving. Data, Data management, Information management, knowledge management are skills in demand in a university setting, and we as librarians need to know how to adapt these skills and figure out how we best can support when our patrons are asking us. The way to learn from the Carpentry lesson material is easy, and the 'real workflow' when conducting research (processes/methods) is outlined in the lessons from the Carpentries

column74:
A lot of the topics are very academic and specific, more mundane classes that people can incorporate into their everyday lives would be useful. There are people in academia who aren't academics, who nonetheless work with lots of data; skills and practices target at them might reach more people. 
More LIS topics would be helpful as well, especially from a technical services perspective. Record management/manipulation, normalization rules, working with metadata, etc. would be useful.
column75: Making sure that there is a full and complete key, with annotations, for all of the carpentries. I worked through a few of the carpentries on my own at the prompting of a carpentries instructor; some of python was wrong to the point that my computer and data scientist colleagues couldn't figure it out. It's hard for students and the instructor if the directions don't match up with data, especially for the less experienced.

column74: I helped develop a new lesson using litsearchr to teach R in an evidence synthesis context (currently in pre-alpha stage). I'd be very interested in working with others to develop more Library Carpentries content related to the automation of systematic review tasks.
column76: As a librarian at a member institution, I have had the opportunity to attend many Carpentries trainings as a student, helper and organizer. Through Carpentries I  gained confidence to take on research projects requiring coding, which has allowed me to vastly improve my skills in R and better support and communicate with faculty and students on our campus.
